The simplest sort of signal is a \\textbf{periodic signal}, in which the same signal pattern repeats over time. Figure 3.2 shows an example of a periodic continuous signal (sine wave) and a periodic discrete signal (square wave). Mathematically, a signal $s(t)$ is defined to be periodic if and only if
\\begin{equation}
s(t+T) = s(t) \\quad -\\infty < t < +\\infty
\\end{equation}
where the constant $T$ is the period of the signal ($T$ is the smallest value that satisfies the equation). Otherwise, a signal is \\textbf{aperiodic}.

The sine wave is the fundamental periodic signal. A general sine wave can be represented by three parameters: peak amplitude ($A$), frequency ($f$), and phase ($\\phi$). The \\textbf{peak amplitude} is the maximum value or strength of the signal over time; typically, this value is measured in volts. The \\textbf{frequency} is the rate [in cycles per second, or hertz (Hz)] at which the signal repeats. An equivalent parameter is the \\textbf{period} ($T$) of a signal, which is the amount of time it takes for one repetition; therefore, $T = 1/f$. \\textbf{Phase} is a measure of the relative position in time within a single period of a signal, as is illustrated subsequently. More formally, for a periodic signal $f(t)$, phase is the fractional part $t/T$ of the period $T$ through which $t$ has advanced relative to an arbitrary origin. The origin is usually taken as the last previous passage through zero from the negative to the positive direction.

The general sine wave can be written
\\begin{equation}
s(t) = A\\sin(2\\pi f t + \\phi)
\\end{equation}
A function with the form of the preceding equation is known as a \\textbf{sinusoid}. Figure 3.3 shows the effect of varying each of the three parameters. In part (a) of

