\\begin{example}
In the United States, ordinary household current is typically supplied at a frequency of 60 Hz with a peak voltage of about 170 V. Thus the power line voltage can be expressed as
\\[
170\\sin\\left(2\\pi \\times 60 \\times t\\right)
\\]
The period of this current is $1/60 = 0.0167$ s = 16.7 ms. A typical velocity of propagation is about 0.9 c, so the wavelength of the current is $\\lambda = vT = 0.9 \\times 3 \\times 10^8 \\times 0.0167 = 4.5 \\times 10^6$ m = 4500 km.

Household voltage is normally stated as being 120 V. This is what is known as the root mean square (square the voltage to make everything positive, find the average, take the square root) value. For a sine wave, the value is calculated as $\\sqrt{(A^2 - 0)/2} = 0.707A$. In this case, $0.707 \\times 170 = 120$.
