encoding schemes. Recall from Chapter 5 that coding can be used to reduce the required $E_b/N_0$ value to achieve a given bit error rate.\\footnote{$E_b/N_0$ is the ratio of signal energy per bit to noise power density per Hz; it is defined and discussed in Chapter 3.} The coding discussed in Chapter 5 has to do with the definition of signal elements to represent bits. The coding discussed in this chapter also has an effect on $E_b/N_0$. In Figure~\\ref{fig:6.9}, the curve on the right is for an uncoded modulation system. To the left of that curve is the area in which improvement can be achieved. In this region, a smaller BER (bit error rate) is achieved for a given $E_b/N_0$, and conversely, for a given BER, a smaller $E_b/N_0$ is required. The other curve is a typical result of a code rate of one-half (equal number of data and check bits). Note that at an error rate of $10^{-6}$, the use of coding allows a reduction in $E_b/N_0$ of 2.77 dB. This reduction is referred to as the \\textbf{coding gain}, which is defined as the reduction, in decibels, in the required $E_b/N_0$ to achieve a specified BER of an error-correcting coded system compared to an uncoded system using the same modulation.

It is important to realize that the BER for the second rate 1/2 curve refers to the rate of uncorrected errors and that the $E_b$ value refers to the energy per data bit.

