Figure~\\ref{fig:ieee8023mac} depicts the frame format for all three types of frames; the differences are contained in the MAC Client Data field. Several additional fields encapsulate the frame to form an 802.3 packet. The fields are as follows:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{Preamble:} A 7-octet pattern of alternating 0s and 1s used by the receiver to establish bit synchronization.
    \\item \\textbf{Start Frame Delimiter (SFD):} The sequence 10101011, which delimits the actual start of the frame and enables the receiver to locate the first bit of the frame.
    \\item \\textbf{Destination Address (DA):} Specifies the station(s) for which the frame is intended. It may be a unique physical address, a multicast address, or a broadcast address.
    \\item \\textbf{Source Address (SA):} Specifies the station that sent the frame.
    \\item \\textbf{Length/Type:} Takes on one of two meanings, depending on its numeric value. If the value of this field is less than or equal to 1500 decimal, then the Length/Type field indicates the number of MAC Client Data octets contained in the subsequent MAC Client Data field (length interpretation).
\\end{itemize}

\\end{document}

\\section{Frame bursting:} This feature allows for multiple short frames to be transmitted consecutively, up to a limit, without relinquishing control for CSMA/CD between frames. Frame bursting avoids the overhead of carrier extension when a single station has a number of small frames ready to send.

With a switching hub (Figure 11.11c), which provides dedicated access to the medium, the carrier extension and frame bursting features are not needed. This is because data transmission and reception at a station can occur simultaneously without interference and with no contention for a shared medium.

\\subsection*{Physical Layer} The 1-Gbps specification for IEEE 802.3 includes the following physical layer alternatives (Figure 12.5):

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{1000BASE-SX:} This short-wavelength option supports duplex links of up to 275 m using 62.5-$\\mu$m multimode or up to 550 m using 50-$\\mu$m multimode fiber. Wavelengths are in the range of 770 to 860 nm.
    \\item \\textbf{1000BASE-LX:} This long-wavelength option supports duplex links of up to 550 m of 62.5-$\\mu$m or 50-$\\mu$m multimode fiber or 5 km of 10-$\\mu$m single-mode fiber. Wavelengths are in the range of 1270 to 1355 nm.
    \\item \\textbf{1000BASE-CX:} This option supports 1-Gbps links among devices located within a single room or equipment rack, using copper jumpers (specialized shielded twisted-pair cable that spans no more than 25 m). Each link is composed of a separate shielded twisted pair running in each direction.
    \\item \\textbf{1000BASE-T:} This option makes use of four pairs of Category 5 unshielded twisted pair to support devices over a range of up to 100 m, transmitting and receiving on all four pairs at the same time, with echo cancellation circuitry.
\\end{itemize}

