\\section*{402}

In 2007, the IEEE 802.3 working group authorized the \\textit{IEEE P802.3ba 40Gb/s and 100Gb/s Ethernet Task Force}. The 802.3ba project authorization request cited a number of examples of applications that require greater data rate capacity than 10-Gbps Ethernet offers, including internet exchanges, high performance computing and video-on-demand delivery. The authorization request justified the need for two different data rates in the new standard (40 Gbps and 100 Gbps) by recognizing that aggregate network requirements and end-station requirements are increasing at different rates.

The first products in this category appeared in 2009, and the IEEE 802.3ba standard was finalized in 2010.

