\\caption{11-Mbps CCK Modulation Scheme}
\\label{fig:13.9}
\\end{figure}

To achieve a higher data rate in the same bandwidth at the same chipping rate, a modulation scheme known as \\textbf{complementary code keying (CCK)} is used.

The CCK modulation scheme is quite complex and is not examined in detail here. Figure~\\ref{fig:13.9} provides an overview of the scheme for the 11-Mbps rate. Input data are treated in blocks of 8 bits at a rate of 1.375 MHz ($8\\,\\text{bits}/\\text{symbol} \\times 1.375\\,\\text{MHz} = 11\\,\\text{Mbps}$). Six of these bits are mapped into one of 64 code sequences derived from a $64 \\times 64$ matrix known as the Walsh matrix (discussed in Chapter 17). The output of the mapping, plus the two additional bits, forms the input to a QPSK (quadrature phase shift keying) modulator.

An optional alternative to CCK is known as packet binary convolutional coding (PBCC). PBCC provides for potentially more efficient transmission at the cost of increased computation at the receiver. PBCC was incorporated into 802.11b in anticipation of its need for higher data rates for future enhancements to the standard.

\\subsection*{Physical-Layer Frame Structure}

IEEE 802.11b defines two physical-layer frame formats, which differ only in the length of the preamble. The long preamble of 144 bits is the same as used in the original 802.11 DSSS scheme and allows interoperability with other legacy systems. The short preamble of 72 bits provides improved throughput efficiency. Figure~\\ref{fig:13.10b} illustrates the physical-layer frame format with the short preamble. The \\textbf{PLCP (physical layer conversion protocol) Preamble} field enables the receiver to acquire an incoming signal and synchronize the demodulator. It consists of two subfields: a 56-bit \\textbf{Sync} field for synchronization and a 16-bit start-of-frame delimiter (\\textbf{SFD}). The preamble is transmitted at 1 Mbps using differential BPSK and Barker code spreading.

Following the preamble is the \\textbf{PLCP Header}, which is transmitted at 2 Mbps using DQPSK. It consists of the following subfields:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{Signal:} Specifies the data rate at which the MPDU (MAC protocol data unit) portion of the frame is transmitted.
    \\item \\textbf{Service:} Only 3 bits of this 8-bit field are used in 802.11b. One bit indicates whether the transmit frequency and symbol clocks use the same local oscillator. Another bit indicates whether CCK or PBCC encoding is used. A third bit acts as an extension to the Length subfield.
\\end{itemize}

