    \\item \\textbf{CRC:} A 16-bit error-detection code used to protect the Signal, Service, and Length fields.
\\end{itemize}

The \\textbf{MPDU} field consists of a variable number of bits transmitted at the data rate specified in the Signal subfield. Prior to transmission, all of the bits of the physical-layer PDU are scrambled (see Appendix 12B for a discussion of scrambling).

\\section*{IEEE 802.11a}

Although 802.11b achieved a certain level of success, its limited data rate results in limited appeal. To meet the needs for a truly high-speed WLAN, IEEE 802.11a was developed.

\\subsection*{Channel Structure}

IEEE 802.11a makes use of the frequency band called the Universal Networking Information Infrastructure (UNNI), which is divided into three parts. The UNNI-1 band (5.15--5.25 GHz) is intended for indoor use; the UNNI-2 band (5.25--5.35 GHz) can be used either indoor or outdoor; and the UNNI-3 band (5.725--5.825 GHz) is for outdoor use.

