\\subsection*{Connection Establishment and Termination}
Even with a reliable network service, there is a need for connection establishment and termination procedures to support connection-oriented service. Connection establishment serves three main purposes:
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item It allows each end to assure that the other exists.
    \\item It allows exchange or negotiation of optional parameters (e.g., maximum segment size, maximum window size, quality of service).
    \\item It triggers allocation of transport entity resources (e.g., buffer space, entry in connection table).
\\end{itemize}

Connection establishment is by mutual agreement and can be accomplished by a simple set of user commands and control segments, as shown in the state diagram of Figure~\\ref{fig:15.3}. To begin, a TS user is in a \\texttt{CLOSED} state (i.e., it has no open transport connection). The TS user can signal to the local TCP entity that it will passively wait for a request with a \\texttt{Passive Open} command. A server program, such as time-sharing or a file transfer application, might do this. After the \\texttt{Passive Open} command is issued, the transport entity creates a connection object of some sort.

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \\centering
    \\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_8.jpeg}
    \\caption{Simple Connection State Diagram}
    \\label{fig:15.3}
\\end{figure}

\\textbf{Figure 15.3} Simple Connection State Diagram

\\documentclass{article}
\\usepackage{graphicx}
\\usepackage{amsmath}
\\usepackage{amssymb}

\\begin{document}

(i.e., a table entry) that is in the LISTEN state. The TS user may then change its mind by sending a Close command.

From the CLOSED state, a TS user may open a connection by issuing an Active Open command, which instructs the transport entity to attempt connection establishment with a designated remote TS user, which triggers the transport entity to send a SYN (for synchronize) segment. This segment is carried to the receiving transport entity and interpreted as a request for connection to a particular port. If the destination transport entity is in the LISTEN state for that port, then a connection is established by the following actions by the receiving transport entity:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item Signal the local TS user that a connection is open.
    \\item Send a SYN as confirmation to the remote transport entity.
    \\item Put the connection object in an ESTAB (established) state.
\\end{itemize}

When the responding SYN is received by the initiating transport entity, it too can move the connection to an ESTAB state. The connection is prematurely aborted if either TS user issues a Close command.

Figure 15.4 shows the robustness of this protocol. Either side can initiate a connection. Further, if both sides initiate the connection at about the same time, it is established without confusion. This is because the SYN segment functions both as a connection request and a connection acknowledgment.

The reader may ask what happens if a SYN comes in while the requested TS user is idle (not listening). Three courses may be followed:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item The transport entity can reject the request by sending a RST (reset) segment back to the other transport entity.
    \\item The request can be queued until the local TS user issues a matching Open.
    \\item The transport entity can interrupt or otherwise signal the local TS user to notify it of a pending request.
\\end{itemize}

