\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{BGP Message Formats}
\\label{fig:bgp_formats}
\\end{figure}

To acquire a neighbor, a router first opens a TCP connection to the neighbor router of interest. It then sends an Open message. This message identifies the AS to which the sender belongs and provides the IP address of the router. It also includes a Hold Time parameter, which indicates the number of seconds that the sender proposes for the value of the Hold Timer. If the recipient is prepared to open a neighbor relationship, it calculates a value of Hold Timer that is the minimum of its Hold Time and the Hold Time in the Open message. This calculated value is the maximum number of seconds that may elapse between the receipt of successive Keepalive and/or Update messages by the sender.

\\end{document}

\\subsection{Edges are of two types:}
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item Graph edges that connect two router vertices when the corresponding routers are connected to each other by a direct point-to-point link
    \\item Graph edges that connect a router vertex to a network vertex when the router is directly connected to the network
\\end{enumerate}

Figure 19.11, based on one in RFC 2328, shows an example of an autonomous system, and Figure 19.12 is the resulting directed graph. The mapping is straightforward:
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item Two routers joined by a point-to-point link are represented in the graph as being directly connected by a pair of edges, one in each direction (e.g., routers 6 and 10).
    \\item When multiple routers are attached to a network (such as a LAN or packet-switching network), the directed graph shows all routers bidirectionally
\\end{itemize}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \\centering
    \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_8.jpeg}
