packet carries a sequence number that is incremented by one per packet. Finally, either side may terminate that connection. Note that both the initiation and termination phases involve three-way handshakes.

A single sequence number is maintained in each direction for all ten types of packets. The following exchange between DCCP entities A and B is an example:

\\begin{align*}
\\text{A} \\to \\text{B}: &\\ \\text{DCCP-Data(seqno=1)} \\\\
\\text{A} \\to \\text{B}: &\\ \\text{DCCP-Data(seqno=2)} \\\\
\\text{B} \\to \\text{A}: &\\ \\text{DCCP-Ack(seqno=10, ackno = 2)} \\\\
\\text{A} \\to \\text{B}: &\\ \\text{DCCP-DataAck(seqno=3, ackno = 10)} \\\\
\\text{B} \\to \\text{A}: &\\ \\text{DCCP-DataACK(seqno=11, ackno=3)}
\\end{align*}

The first two lines show that A sends two packets to B, numbered 1 and 2. Then B sends a pure acknowledgment with a sequence number of 10 and an acknowledgment of the last received packet. With A's next data packet, it increments its own sequence number and acknowledges the last packed from B by including an acknowledgment number. B's next packet is a data packet with a sequence number and an acknowledgment number. The use of a single sequence numbering scheme for all three types of packets enables the endpoints to detect all packet loss, including acknowledgment loss.

Since DCCP provides unreliable semantics, there are no retransmissions, and having a TCP-style cumulative acknowledgment field doesn't make sense. DCCP's

