\\subsection{DNS Operation}
DNS operation typically includes the following steps (Figure 24.6):
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item A user program requests an IP address for a domain name.
    \\item A resolver module in the local host or local ISP queries a local name server in the same domain as the resolver.
    \\item The local name server checks to see if the name is in its local database or cache, and, if so, returns the IP address to the requestor. Otherwise, the name server queries other available name servers, if necessary going to the root server, as explained subsequently.
    \\item When a response is received at the local name server, it stores the name/ address mapping in its local cache and may maintain this entry for the amount of time specified in the time to live field of the retrieved RR.
    \\item The user program is given the IP address or an error message.
\\end{enumerate}

