\\subsection{RTP Data Transfer Protocol}
We first look at the basic concepts of the RTP data transfer protocol and then examine the protocol header format. Throughout this section, the term \\textit{RTP} will refer to the RTP data transfer protocol.

\\textbf{RTP Concepts} RTP supports the transfer of real-time data among a number of participants in a session. A session is simply a logical association among two or more RTP entities that is maintained for the duration of the data transfer. A session is defined by the following:
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{RTP port number:} The destination port address is used by all participants for RTP transfers. If UDP is the lower layer, this port number appears in the Destination Port field (see Figure 2.6) of the UDP header.
\\end{itemize}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{RTP Header}
\\label{fig:rtp_header}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item An application-level firewall may prevent the forwarding of RTP packets. Two translators are used, one on each side of the firewall, with the outside one tunneling all multicast packets received through a secure connection to the translator inside the firewall. The inside translator then sends out RTP packets to a multicast group protected by the firewall.
    \\item A translator can replicate an incoming multicast RTP packet and send it to a number of unicast destinations.
\\end{itemize}

\\textbf{RTP Fixed Header} Each RTP packet includes a fixed header and may also include additional application-specific header fields. Figure~\\ref{fig:rtp_header} shows the fixed header. The first 12 octets (shaded portion) are always present and consist of the following fields:

\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\textbf{Version (2 bits):} Current version is 2.
    \\item \\textbf{Padding (1 bit):} Indicates whether padding octets appear at the end of the payload. If so, the last octet of the payload contains a count of the number of padding octets. Padding is used if the application requires that the payload be an integer multiple of some length, such as 32 bits.
    \\item \\textbf{Extension (1 bit):} If set, the fixed header is followed by exactly one extension header, which is used for experimental extensions to RTP.
    \\item \\textbf{CSRC Count (4 bits):} The number of CSRC (contributing source) identifiers that follow the fixed header.
    \\item \\textbf{Marker (1 bit):} The interpretation of the marker bit depends on the payload type; it is typically used to indicate a boundary in the data stream. For video, it is set to mark the end of a frame. For audio, it is set to mark the beginning of a talk spurt.
    \\item \\textbf{Payload Type (7 bits):} Identifies the format of the RTP payload, which follows the RTP header.
\\end{itemize}

